In [18]:
# normality test
from scipy.stats import shapiro
stat, p = shapiro(seg_1['sales'])
print('Statistics=%.5f, p=%.5f' % (stat, p))
# interpret
alpha = 0.05
if p > alpha:
 print('Sample looks Gaussian (fail to reject H0)')
else:
 print('Sample does not look Gaussian (reject H0)')

In [ ]:
In [19]:
import pylab
stats.probplot(seg_1.sales,plot=pylab);

The X-axis of the above plot has Quantiles values and Y-axis has the sales values. From the plot, we can analyze that the data points of the price feature are not falling on a straight line. This implies that it does not follow a normal distribution.

In [20]:
import scipy.stats as stats
import pylab
#function to return plots for the feature
def normality(seg_1,feature):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    sns.kdeplot(seg_1[feature])
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    stats.probplot(seg_1[feature],plot=pylab)
    plt.show()

In [38]:
def segment(a):
    df=data[(data['SIAM Segment 1']==a)]
    df=df[['sales','YrMth','Month']]
    seg=df.groupby(['YrMth']).sum('sales')
    return seg

def time_series(df):
    #df=df[['sales','YrMth']]
    #df.set_index('YrMth',inplace=True)
    rolmean=df.rolling(window=7).mean()
    rolstd=df.rolling(window=7).std()
    df.plot(figsize=(20,10))
    plt.title("sales")
    #plt.xlabels('')
    #plt.ylabels('')
    plt.grid()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.plot(df,color='blue',label='Orginal')
    plt.plot(rolmean,color='red',label='rolling mean')
    plt.plot(rolstd,color='green',label='rolling std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()
    from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import acf,pacf
    lag_acf=acf(df,nlags=12)
    p=lag_acf[0].astype(int)
    lag_pacf=pacf(df,nlags=12,method='ols')
    q=lag_acf[0].astype(int)
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.plot(lag_acf)
    plt.axhline(y=0,linestyle='--',color='gray')
    plt.axhline(y=1.96/np.sqrt(len(df)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
    plt.axhline(y=1.96/np.sqrt(len(df)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
    plt.title('Autocorrelation Function')
    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.plot(lag_pacf)
    plt.axhline(y=0,linestyle='--',color='gray')
    plt.axhline(y=1.96/np.sqrt(len(df)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
    plt.axhline(y=1.96/np.sqrt(len(df)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
    plt.title('partial Autocorrelation Function')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
    model=ARIMA(df,order=(p,1,q))
    results_AR=model.fit()
    plt.plot(df)
    plt.plot(results_AR.fittedvalues,color='red')
    plt.title('RSS: %.4f'% sum((results_AR.fittedvalues-df['sales'])**2))
    plt.show()
    prediction=pd.Series(results_AR.fittedvalues,copy=True)
    prediction_cum=prediction.cumsum()
    predictions=pd.Series(df['sales'],index=df.index)
    predictions=predictions.add(prediction_cum,fill_value=0)
    import matplotlib as mpl
    mpl.rcParams['agg.path.chunksize'] = 100
    predictions_arima=np.exp(predictions)
    print(predictions)
    plt.plot(df)
    plt.plot(predictions)
    forecasts = results_AR.forecast(steps=6)
    print(forecasts)

In [45]:
def adf_test(series):
    result=adfuller(series)
    print('ADF Statistics: {}'.format(result[0]))
    print('p-value: {}'.format(result[1]))
    if result[1]<=0.05:
        print('Strong evidence against the null hypothesis,reject the null hypothesis. Data has no unit root and is stationary')
    else:
        print('weak evidence against the null hypothesis,time series has unit root, indicating is stationary')
